% =====================================================================
\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

% DRAFT — will be expanded once results are available
We proposed \popw{}, a unified architecture for multi-task assembly understanding. The main ideas are: (1) sharing a ConvNeXt-Tiny backbone across detection, pose, activity, and PSR; (2) a two-stage FiLM design that passes pose information to the activity head without gradient feedback; and (3) staged training with Kendall weighting to keep optimization stable. Full results and comparisons against baselines will be added once training finishes~\popwres.

% =====================================================================
\section{Limitations}
\label{sec:limitations}

% DRAFT — likely to grow as we discover more issues during training
A few limitations we are aware of at this stage. First, the backbone is single-frame only---the temporal reasoning is delegated to feature banks and a causal transformer, which is less expressive than video-native backbones like VideoMAE or TimeSformer. Adding one would push params from 53.3M to 75.3M. Second, we use RGB only, while the MViTv2 baseline on IndustReal also uses vision-language features and stereo depth. Third, Kendall weighting can be sensitive to initialization and may saturate---clamping log-variances to [-4, 2] helps but UW-SO or gradient-based methods might be more stable. Fourth, pose heads need ground-truth labels that not all datasets provide. Fifth, everything runs on a single RTX 3060; scaling up would need more engineering.

% =====================================================================
\section{Broader Impact}
\label{sec:impact}

% DRAFT — brief placeholder to show we've thought about this
This work could help make assembly monitoring more accessible by running on consumer GPUs. Potential upsides: quality control, training feedback, production optimization. Potential concerns: worker surveillance, pressure from automated tracking. We think the system should be used for task verification, not performance evaluation, and any deployment needs clear policies and worker consent.

